{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014wegH8SNEpoC1QeDzqXmK6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The logic: If any of C, D, E has a name, use it. But if multiple have names, that's an \"ERROR\". If none have names, use B.\n\nLooking at the examples:\n- Row 2: C=Jim, D=None, E=None → Jim (one new employee)\n- Row 3: C=None, D=None, E=David → David\n- Row 5: C=None, D=None, E=None → Connor (default to B)\n- Row 6: C=None, D=Jeremy, E=Kathy → ERROR (multiple new employees)\n\nSo the formula needs to:\n\n\nCount how many cells in C, D, E are filled, then return \"ERROR\" if more than one is populated, the single name if exactly one is filled, or fall back to B if all three are empty. I can use COUNTA to check the count and CONCAT to extract the one non-blank value since concatenating with blanks just gives the non-blank cell.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":921,"cache_read_input_tokens":13716,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":921},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9911056a-30c0-4c4c-b988-ee21d610c72d","uuid":"bcb8e21d-0308-4939-ab98-9a59a8ef2d05"}
